Overall, LGTM. 

With the support of OCI, I am wondering at which point this is necessary.

@blakepettersson do you think this can all be solved with OCI and what would be the steps to perform for a user to switch from using a help repo to OCI? Is that possible and can it be a transparent migration for the users (no change in the Application, only in the Repository)? Could it imply modifying the registry itself? I am not super familiar with OCI applications and the examples are sparse.

Thanks for the PR!
Please note that now apps in all namespaces are returned, and some of those namespaces might not be watched at the controller level (meaning, not allowed in the config map).
```	
appsCount := 0
	for i := range apps {
		if apps[i].Spec.GetProject() == proj.Name {
			appsCount++
		}
	}   
```
So in the above existing code, another check needs to be added - that the ns of the app is allowed, otherwise this app is not relevant for the decision whether to finalize the project deletion.
This can be used for the check:
``` isAppNamespaceAllowed ``` in appcontroller.go

Looking at the code related to the `done` channel I see this
```
                              else {
					sentCount++
					if err := ws.Send(&application.LogEntry{
						PodName:      &entry.podName,
						Content:      &entry.line,
						TimeStampStr: pointer.String(entry.timeStamp.Format(time.RFC3339Nano)),
						TimeStamp:    &ts,
						Last:         pointer.Bool(false),
					}); err != nil {
						done <- err
						break
					}
```
This should probably be a return too because if the loop just breaks then there's another write to the done channel outside the loop which may block in case the context already ends so either the buffer has to be of size 2 or this needs to be a return instead of a break.

@hille721 I don't think that just changing `==` to `>=` would fix the issue you are describing.
If there are multiple hosts included as part of the Ingress spec, then status for each host should have all the conditions to be `True`. 

Your check will fail if one host has both status conditions `false` and one host has both conditions `true`. In this case the status will still show as `Healthy` wherein it needs to be `Degraded`.

@hille721 WDYT?
